5000|$|The {{total return}} on a {{portfolio}} of investments takes into account not only the capital appreciation on the portfolio, but also the income received on the portfolio. The income typically consists of interest, dividends, and <b>securities</b> <b>lending</b> <b>fees.</b> This contrasts with the price return, which takes into account only the capital gain on an investment. In 2010 an academic paper highlighted this issue found with most web charts in the 'compare' mode, and {{was published in the}} Journal of Behavioral Finance. The discrepancy between total return charts and [...] "price only" [...] charts was later brought out in the Wall Street Journal.|$|R
