40|$|Working with a sizeable, {{anonymous}} money manager, we randomly {{make available}} for lending {{two-thirds of the}} high-loan fee stocks in the managerâ€™s portfolio and withhold the other third to produce an exogenous shock to loan supply. We implement the lending experiment in two independent phases: the first, from September 5 to 18, 2008, with over $ 580 million of securities lent; and the second, from June 5 to September 30, 2009, with over $ 250 million of securities lent. The supply shocks are sizeable and significantly reduce <b>lending</b> <b>fees,</b> but returns, volatility, skewness, and bid-ask spreads remain unaffected. Results are consistent across both phases of the experiment and indicate no adverse effects from <b>securities</b> <b>lending</b> on stock prices. ...|$|R
